metadata.name: Foundations #281
metadata.description:
In march of this year, I started working on a new series involving multi-layering, and overriding shapes. Drawing and playing with colors and opacity.
It started with squares and grid, it then involved deformations, and circles and other experimentations.
This path fits with my artistic generative approach: rather than having a completely predefined idea, I start with a simple concept that evolves during creation. Then surprises happened, and I embraced them.

But this year was not like any other: 2022 has gifted me with a new birthday, the one of my son.

Over the past twelve months, I’ve watched him discovering the world surrounding him, learning and trying new things, laughing, or getting frustrated, sad or happy…
While learning to become a parent, I’ve been in an introspection phase where I questioned what it means to be “a father”. What impact will I have on my son, consciously or not?

“Foundations” takes shape in this context: 2 humans trying and exploring while being inspired by each other.
This series is a first of a set of at least 3, that illustrates an idea of what is an “Identity”, and what makes us who we are.

The foundations of an identity are laid in the first days of a child’s life. They will be influenced by many factors; including parenting, cultural environment, life experiences… 
Of course, as humans we are in constant evolution; life happens, sometimes for the best, sometimes for the worst, and our personality will be impacted…
But this will be a topic for another time. 


Today, we are at the start.

metadata.name: Element #148
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

Where life is less burdensome,
Where all gaze upon me, unaware
Of my presence in this lunar realm.

Connected to others, despite being unseen."

metadata.name: KINJO! #381
metadata.description:
A celebration of my 1 year in the Tezos art space, KINJO is an experiment in pure abstraction and randomness. With a simple grid at its core, this piece attempts to play with lively colors, completely unique variations, and host the nice surprises that randomness can bring.

My intention when starting to work in the Tezos space was to play with the surrender of control in art, that idea had always fascinated me. In the beginning it was working with GAN, digitally painting a piece or processing my own photography, and sending it through my own frankensteined colab notebook. I was creating something and then trusting a process to rip it apart and create something new. I moved on to the Ganerations project, which was essentially gen art in layered pngs and processed through my GAN notebook. I found generative art and fxHash shortly after and have been incredibly thankful for the community here, as well as inspired every day by the new approaches I see from both new and established artists on the platform. I'm learning every day.

Gen art is the perfect place for me to express myself and explore the themes of control and trust with my work, and I thank you all for following along and supporting my work :)

Just an ordinary scene from a typical day, working as a Sprocket Factory engineer. Inspiration for this work is drawn from the composable nature of blockchain smart contracts and the flow of value between networks of autonomous machines and free-willed individuals.
